I"<p>Similar to how <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/constructivism-fosters-understanding-through-scaffolding">backlinks are a proxy for how “fundamental” a note is</a>, <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/tense-logic-formalizes-time">time</a> can also inform the <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/how-could-core-concepts-be-identified">search for core items</a>. If a document was created in a certain <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/spatial-metaphors-provide-primitives-for-latent-space-navigation">region of semantic space</a> (e.g. the original <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/few-shot-learning-exapts-text-generation">transformers</a> paper), only to be followed by a bunch of new documents in the same region soon afterwards (e.g. papers applying transformers to low-hanging fruit tasks), then it could be labeled as “pioneering” and “<a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/powerful-seach-capabilities-reduce-friction-in-note-taking">relevant</a>.”</p>
